    "is_good_patch": true,
    "synth_pr": "\n## Title: Fix VCD timing when ENABLE_USE_CPU_EXECUTION_TIME not defined\n\n### Summary\nThe VCD signal dumper module produces incorrect timing information when compiled with `ENABLE_VCD_FIFO` but without `ENABLE_USE_CPU_EXECUTION_TIME`. In this configuration, the `vcd_get_time()` function always returns zero, causing all VCD events to appear to occur simultaneously. This makes timing analysis impossible and can lead to misinterpretation of function call sequences and performance bottlenecks.\n\nThe issue manifests as flat timing traces in GTKWave where all signal transitions occur at timestamp 0, regardless of actual execution time. Users reported that VCD traces showed no meaningful timing differences between function calls, even when significant processing delays were expected.\n\nRoot cause was the `vcd_get_time()` function returning a hardcoded 0 when `ENABLE_USE_CPU_EXECUTION_TIME` was not defined, instead of falling back to a working timing mechanism. The fix ensures `clock_gettime(CLOCK_MONOTONIC, ...)` is used consistently for timing regardless of the execution time feature flag.\n\n### Changes\n- `common/utils/LOG/vcd_signal_dumper.c`: Made `g_time_start` initialization unconditional and updated `vcd_get_time()` to always use `clock_gettime()` for proper timing\n- `common/utils/LOG/vcd_signal_dumper.c`: Removed conditional compilation around timing functions to ensure consistent behavior\n"
}